review_blob:
Seriously, Im rating this beer this higly because it is just that good. It is my favorite beer and I think you should give it a shot.  Its a wheat beer (Golden to be exact), so dont expect a very robust taste.  It has an added rasberry flavor to it, which I found a bit unnerving before I tried it but very appealing after my first sip.  One problem, however, is the inconsistancy with the brew.  Sometimes it has a lighter rasberry flavor, and sometimes it has a much more present rasberry flavor.  If you dont like it the first time you try it, try it again a month or so later and you might have a brew from a different batch.  The batches from the kegs tend to have a much more present rasberry taste and a smoother feel to it. 
But to put it succinctly, Ill order this beer anytime I see it in a bar.
Blah...Averedge beer. Not too great, not too bad.  Doesnt taste a damn thing like a pale ale.

Heres the deal with coors. The ligher they make it, the shittier it is.  Now i loved drinking hippi piss in high school, but I think Ill leave those days to yesteryear.  For products in this price range, go with a bud.

Tastes much more like the wheats ive had in Europe than the the ones Ive had in the states, but it is quite good.  Tastes very simmilar to Paulanzer if you like that.  I definately couldnt have more than one or two at a time because its extremely rich and actually a  bit spicy.
Wow - Great Taste!  Very fruity but not overpowering.  More of something to drink on ocassion because it is a little sweet.
Wow - Very bitter.  Its the kind of beer that you cant have after a clean or light beer because it is SO bitter.  Taste is good but I think I had it from a bad tap.
WOW - Increadibly great texture.  Good amber taste.  Lots of sweet aroma.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: It doesnt taste much like a wheat, but the honey taste is very well done.  A little heaver than what I was expecting in a wheat.

The vanilla taste is very present but not overpowering.  It doesnt taste nearly as heavy as it looks, possibly because of the light vanilla taste.  Another simmilar vanilla beer is Bohannons Vanilla Cream Ale (although Bohannons is much lighter).

If the bottle didnt have the word "honey" on it, I probably wouldnt have known to look for the honey taste.  The beer is very light and weak, even for a wheat.  Doesent taste much like a wheat either - im a bit skeptical.
One of Sam Adams best beers.  Increadible color/look and very aromatic.  Not as bitter as most bocks but it all depends on what you like.
The taste is ok but the aroma is messed up by how tart it is and the strange carbonation.  The aftertaste is gross and watery because there is somethign about the carbonation that makes it sting.
Very good bock, although I had it directly from the tap at the brewery so I dont know if its the same in the bottle.  Very dark and a great bitter aftertaste.
Better than almost all light beers, although it doesnt taste all that light.  Like its not-light counterpart, its body is fuller than it looks.  Very hopsy.
Better than Budweiser, and much cleaner/smoother.  Dont let the color fool you - the body is a bit fuller than the color would show.  Very malty.
Increadible pilsner with a lasting bitter aftertaste.   Great head - very frothy.

Simmilar to Heineken but less flavor and not so much bite.  Somewhat smooth.
Nothing in it that is distinctively great.

I really dont like the metallic taste that comes from this beer (and no, Im not taking just a sample from a can).  Its decent and very drinkable, but not my favorite.  A bit too thin and watery as well.  Flavor is kind of distinctive, saving its otherwise bad impression on me.
I like it much better than the regular Heineken, but it still has that sour/bitter aftertaste to it.  The only thing that this beer offers that regular heineken doesnt offer is a better aroma.
Worst mexican beer ever.  I could describe its wonderfull aroma, but im an honest man, so no.

Very impressive pilsner, and what is even more impressive is that I found it in one of the biggest shithole of bars in the world.  Tried it just to see what the supposed first pilsner ever was like and was very pleased.  The hype behind it was probably the best quality of the beer, but the aroma and taste were nothing to complain about one bit.
One of the better popular Mexican Beers, Carta Blanca offers an almost vanilla taste to this light bodied beveredge.  Has that familliar tang that most Mexican beers seem to have.

Very simmilar to the Abita Purple Haze in that it is a wheat beer with added rasberry flavors.  They only make one batch a year for the LA blueberry festival and it is available only there or at the Abita Brew Pub.  
Beer is tart and sweet and even seems to have a sting to it (very carbonated).  Simmilar textures to Purple Haze, but not nearly as good.  Some people, however, that do not like purple haze tend to like this brew.  Go figure.

A MOST impressive stout.  Took about ten minutes to poor (litterally), but worth every sip.  Unfortunately it is only available at the Abita Brew Pub.
Very sweet and chocolaty taste.  Fills you up quite quickly.
Heavy body and very malty.  Make your way to abita springs to try it.  It was formerly called the Jocomo stout, but its name has since been changed (along with a few changes to the recipee)
Excellent pale ale.  More hopps than i expected and a very clean and smooth flavor.

This is a wheat beer that abita produces year round.  Apparently the brewery intends on improving this beer in the next few months with its new machinery.  I had no idea it was a wheat beer untill they told me, but oh well.  At times, it is a bit more appeasing than the amber because it isnt as sweet, but amber remains a better beer. Its a bit thinner, but doesnt leave that certain something to be desired like any other light beer.  Its less of a wheat beer than thier summer wheat, but has more body to it than the wheat.

Wow-This is a lager?  Nice and light body.  Taste is kind of sweet, like lots of tropical lagers.  Decent price even with bottles.  Recently saw this in cans while in Europe and was suprised.  I had one and it wasnt all that good. Stick to the bottles - it makes a big difference.

Like all of the crescent city beers, it tastes a little spicy.  Its not like it has a bite to it, but it leaves a bit of a sting on my throat.  Very drinkable, and probably the smoothest of all the crescent city line.
Medium to thick body, but very smooth going down.  A bit carmely, with very present roasted hops.  Good with meals.
A good vienna style beer, but thinner than most viennas that Ive had.  Still has that spicy taste that I dont quite understand.  Not something I want in a beer, but thats just me.

I can barely find this beer anymore.  Does anyone know what happened to it?  
I suppose the other crappy beers like natty, beast, etc, have taken over the college market.  Nonetheless, it isnt that good of a beer.  Tastes bitter, but a bad kind of bitter.

Not too good for drinking, but believe it or not I actually use this beer for cooking sometimes.  (Sausages, and a tad in red sauces).   I never would have done it except for it is a supposed family secret.  Probably just came about because someone got drunk and mistook the schlitz for something else.
Ugh.....entirely too much bite and it tastes like alcohol, even though its only five percent.  Beware of the next day.  I cant believe that this comes in longnecks.

I like this flavored beer, especially since im a big strawberry fan.  I dont let people give me crap for drinking a flavored beer, because its STILL beer.  
Problems - theres too much strawberry flavor.  Kinda tastes syrupy.  If it were a little bit more suddle, it wouldnt take away from the palate as much.  It isnt as hopsy as Id like either, but you cant get that with a fruit beer I assume.  The aftertaste is more like candy than a beer, but like I said, if there were less flavor, it would be better.  All in all, its a good tasting beer that Id buy again.
For a cheap college beer, this is one of the better ones.  Still, it kinda taste like hippi piss from the colorado rockies.  Dont buy it unless your desperate.

Ugh...bad red dog, Bad.  I remember when this stuff came out about seven years ago and it was a big deal, but it has since found its way to fouty ounce land.  Ugh...nonno.  
On the plus side, the flavor isnt all that bad.

As far as those bad beers go, it isnt all that bad. Its the best of the cheap college beers....a little less bite, but too watery.  Clean taste, which is a plus for a cheap beer.  Still would never buy it though.

I tasted this beer in the states and in England.  Thought it was much better in England. The initial taste was sour in the states, but the aftertaste (the best quality of this particular beer in my opinion) was about the same in the states as it was in Europe. Very expensive too over here, so Id only buy it again if I were in Europe.
The taste is a little sweet and sour.  Could stand to have a bit more head.  Definately not my favorite wheat.
Great beer.  Bitter but sweet flavor to it.  Nice and smooth, with a lot of carbonation.

I have not had too many wheat beers, so I honestly do not have much to compare this too.  I enjoy it a lot, especially since it is almost the same thing as my favorite beer (Abita purple haze - A rasberry-wheat beer), but withouth the rasberries, it just isnt the same.  It is extremely crisp and refreshing, but its aroma leaves something to be desired (possibly because of its thinness).  The flavoring may not be exremely pungent, but the smoothness is incredible (possibly why it makes such a good base for purple haze). Its a seasonal beer, available during the summer between red ale and fall fest.
UPDATE: This years batch is better in my opinion - go try it before its gone.
For an aussie beer, Ill take XXXX because it doesnt ahve that metallic bite that fosters has (out of the tap or not).
Not too much head.  Would be better if it were a bit hopsier.  Apparently its a mass-produced beer, so Im much impressed with their efforts to conserve quality - unlike some American breweries.

I bought a variety pack of flying dog beers, and this one was by far my favorite.  I wasnt terribly impressed by the brewery honestly.  If I were to  buy flying dog again, it would most certainly be this particular brew.  Give it a shot...you may have another opinion.
beer_name: Flying Dog Tire Bite Golden Ale

review_blob: Ugh. Not a fan at all. I feel guilty because a lot of other beer connasseurs tend to enjoy it, but I didnt.  I bot a variety pack with about seven different flying dog brews, and this one was my least favorite.  Oh well...my opinion might be crap.  I probably had a bad batch considering the other reviews. I will give it another try and re-review it shortly.

beer_brewer_name: Vermont Hard Cider Company, LLC (C&C; Group)
review_blob: I dont know that I call this a beer, but whatever.  Its a good cider.  Very fruity, very light, and very sweet.  Goes over well with the ladies as well.  Dont drink too much of these, so I dont have too much of a comparrison.  I still like it.

Run of the mill, b ut still, you cant knock the MGD too much.  A lot more flavor than any of the other miller products, MGD gives a fairly decent taste with a lot of smoothness.  Unfortunately, Miller isnt too flavorfull to begin with.
Great for festivals/ballgames, etc, but not a bar drink at all.  Dont quite understand the big hype over all the miller products, but its a decent light beer.
Wonderfull summer brew with a distinct taste and very aeromatic aftertaste.  Hopsy with a lot of head.  Very smooth finish.
Decent ale.  More of a lagery taste.  Light and creamy taste.

Very smooth and light beer.  Good flavor despite its thinnes.  Much better with a lime in it.  Better than corona - MUCH better.  When I went to Mexico, they said that they keep this beer for themselves and export the corona.
